<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36058h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36058h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36058h"> 58(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Tribes <font face="wake">O</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The new colonies, here alluded to, consisted of several families, whose descendants are known to this day, under the general appellation of the &ldquo;<i><mark>tribes</mark> of Galway</i>,&rdquo; an expression, first invented by Cromwell&apos;s forces, as a term of reproach against the natives of the town, for their singular friendship and attachment to each other during the time of their unparalleled troubles and persecutions, but which, the latter afterwards adopted, as an honorable mark of distinction between themselves and those cruel oppressors. <small> James Hardiman, <a name="JHHT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JHHT"><cite title="source">The History of the Town and County of the Town of Galway</cite></a> (1820, rpt. 1926) 6-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
